MUSA 508 - Targeting A Housing Subsidy in Emil City

Ling Chen

2023/11/2

Introduction

Emil City is considering a more proactive approach for targeting home owners who qualify for a home repair tax credit program. The Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) tries to proactively reach out to eligible homeowners ever year, the uptake of the credit is woefully inadequate. Therefore, in this project, Ill convert the client-level data collected from previous campaigns into a decision-making analytic that can better target their limited outreach resources. By running some logistic regression models, my goal is to train the best classifier and inform a cost/benefit analysis.

The data is adopted from Moro & Rita (2014).

Data Exploration

Data Visualization

Among the continuous variables, individuals who choose to take the credit tend to be contacted before and are slightly older on average. Additionally, many of them experience periods when the employment rate decreases over a quarter compared to the previous quarter. Furthermore, they exhibit a more moderate consumer price index and confidence index in comparison to those who do not take the credit. Simultaneously, they allocate fewer resources to home repairs.

As for the categorical variables, it is evident that individuals contacted by cellular means are more inclined to take the credit. There is no distinct upward trend in credit uptake observed across the days of the week or throughout the year. However, individuals with mortgages, residents of Philadelphia, and those with higher education levels tend to be more likely to take the credit.

Logistic Regression Initial Model

A logistic regression model predicts a binary outcome - a 1 or a 0 - a taking the credit or a Not taking the credit. I partition the data into a 65/35 training and test set.The first model includes all the variables.

housingSubsidyModel <- glm(y_numeric ~ .,
                  data=housingSubsidyTrain %>% 
                    dplyr::select(-X, -y),
                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

Variable Transformations

To enhance the models goodness of fit, certain variables have been reclassified to reduce ambiguity. For instance, the education variable has been restructured into three levels: low, medium, and high. Similarly, the job variable has been redefined into three income categories: low income, medium income, and high income., aiming at achieving a more accurate model representation.

Further, I created a data frame of test set probabilities,which includes both the observed and predicted probabilities for each observation. Upon examination of the tables below, it becomes evident that the models perform well in predicting instances where individuals do not take the credit. However, their predictive performance is less accurate when it comes to identifying those who will take the credit.

Confusion Matrix

The confusion matrix shows the rate at which we got True Positives (Sensitivity), False Positives, True Negatives (Specificity) and False Negatives for the 50% threshold. Specifically,

True Positive - Predicted correctly homeowner would enter credit program; allocated the marketing resources, and 25% ultimately achieved the credit.

True Negative - Predicted correctly homeowner would not enter the credit program, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated.

False Positive - Predicted incorrectly homeowner would enter the credit program; allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated.

False Negative - We predicted that a homeowner would not enter the credit program but they did. These are likely homeowners who signed up for reasons unrelated to the marketing campaign. Thus, we 0 out this category, assuming the cost/benefit of this is $0.

In summary, the overall accuracy of the three models is quite similar, with Model 1 achieving 89.9%, Model 2 achieving 90.3%, and Model 3 achieving 90.6%. All three models excel in predicting individuals who are unlikely to take credit, demonstrating high true negative specificity, particularly Model 3, which achieves an accuracy of over 98.5%. However, none of the three models perform well in predicting those who will take credit, with Model 3 being the relatively better performer, achieving an accuracy of 25.5%, compared to 24.2% for Model 2 and 23.6% for Model 1.

ROC Curve

Furthermore, the ROC curve gives more insights into the models goodness of fit.By The goal is to maximum the area under the curve,which shows that the model is better. By comparison, model 3 has the largest area under curve of 0.786, while model 2 has 0.784 and model 1 has 0.778. As such, model 3 performs best in this situation.

area1 <- auc(testProbs1$Outcome, testProbs1$Probs)
roc1 <- ggplot(testProbs1, aes(d = as.numeric(Outcome), m = Probs)) +
  geom_roc(n.cuts = 50, labels = FALSE, colour = "#FE9900") +
  style_roc(theme = theme_grey) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, size = 1.5, color = 'grey') +
  labs(title = "ROC Curve - Model1")

area2 <-auc(testProbs2$Outcome, testProbs2$Probs)

Cross validation

From the 100-fold cross validation,the ROC (AUC), Sensitivity and Specificity across this series of predicitons still look good. From the cross valiadation goodness of fit metrics, the goal is to have tighter distribution to its mean, showing its generalizability. As we can see, both model 1 and model 3 generalizes well with respect to specificity - the rate it correctly predicts not taking the credit(the true negatives). It does not generalize as well with respect to sensitivity - the rate it correctly predicts taking the credit(true positives).

Cost-Benefit Calculation

Because of higher sensitivity and accuracy, I chose the model 3 to predict. The overall goal is to target home owners who qualify for a home repair tax credit program.

The assumptions are: 25% of contacted eligible homeowners receive the credit, the remaining 75% that receive the marketing allocation and enter the program do not take the credit for various reasons.

True Positive: (-$2,850 + (-$5,000 + $10,000 + $56,000)* 25%) * Count

True Negative: $0

False Positive: -$2,850 * Count

False Negative: $0

Cost-Benefit Table

As depicted in the table using a threshold of 0.5, the revenue from true-positives amounts to $496,000, true-negatives yield $0, false-positives result in a loss of -$54,150, and there are no occurrences of false-negatives. Overall, the gains in the housing markets outweigh the costs.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs3 %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((0.25*(56000+10000-5000)-2850) * Count),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0))))) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We correctly predicted homeowner would enter the credit program; allocated the marketing resources, and 25% ultimately achieved the credit",
              "We correctly predicted homeowner would not enter the credit program, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated",
              "We predicted that a homeowner would not enter the credit program but they did",
              "We predicted incorrectly homeowner would enter the credit program; allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
       caption = "Cost/Benefit Table") %>% kable_styling()

Optimize Thresholds

The last step to tuning our model is to run it for each threshold value. I previously chose 0.5 as the line above which a prediction is classified as taking the credit. From the confusion matrices for each threshold, revenue is calculated for each confusion metric at each threshold. The goal is to choose the one that returns the most revenue.

From the Total_Count_of_Credits as a function of Threshold, we can find that as threshold changes, the % of confusion matrix changes as well.As the threshold increases, the number of false positives decreases, but the number of true negatives increases.

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs3)

whichThreshold %>%
  ggplot(.,aes(Threshold, Count, colour = Variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = palette5) +    
  labs(title = "Total count of credits by confusion matrix type and threshold",
       y = "Count") +
  guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Confusion Matrix"))

By examining the Total_Revenue as a function of the Threshold, it becomes evident that there is a noticeable trend. At a threshold value of approximately 0.1, both negative and positive revenues are observed to decrease. However, at a certain point, they reach their peak values.

whichThreshold %>%
  ggplot(.,aes(Threshold, Revenue, colour = Variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = palette5[c(5, 1:3)]) +    
  labs(title = "Revenue by confusion matrix type and threshold",
       y = "Revenue") +
  guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Confusion Matrix"))

Moreover, the optimal threshold, which yields the highest revenue, is defined to be approximately 0.13.

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs3)

whichThreshold_revenue <- 
whichThreshold %>% 
    group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(Revenue = sum(Revenue))

  ggplot(whichThreshold_revenue)+
  geom_line(aes(x = Threshold, y = Revenue, colour = "#FE9900",linewidth = 0.1))+
  geom_vline(xintercept =  pull(arrange(whichThreshold_revenue, -Revenue)[1,1]))+
    labs(title = "Model Revenues By Threshold For Test Sample",
         subtitle = "Vertical Line Denotes Optimal Threshold")

Total count of credits keep rising as threshold goes up.

whichThreshold_credit <- 
whichThreshold %>% 
  mutate(credit =  ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", (Count * 0.13),
                             ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count, 0))) %>%
  group_by(Threshold) %>% 
  summarize(Credit = sum(credit))

  ggplot(whichThreshold_credit)+
  geom_line(aes(x = Threshold, y = Credit, colour = "#FE9900",linewidth = 0.1))+
  geom_vline(xintercept =  pull(arrange(whichThreshold_credit, -Credit)[1,1]))+
    labs(title = "Total Count of Credits By Threshold For Test Sample",
         subtitle = "Vertical Line Denotes Optimal Threshold")+
  theme(legend.position = "None")

Finally, the table below shows the contrast in revenue and count of credits between the optimal threshold(0.13) and the 0.50 threshold. The optimal threshold maximize revenue, bringing more benefits to the market. However, the number of home owners who take the credit is lower than the threshold of 0.50. In general, from a cost-benefit perspective, I would choose the optimal threshold for the model.

threshold_table <- merge(whichThreshold_revenue, whichThreshold_credit, by = "Threshold")

final_table <- threshold_table %>%
                  slice(13, 50) 

kable(final_table, caption = "Total Revenue and Total Count of Credits for Optimal Threshold and 0.5 Threshold") %>%

Conclusion

In conclusion, I would not recommend deploying this model into production for several reasons. Firstly, the training dataset contains an extremely small number of records for people taking the credits, which significantly affects the models sensitivity, resulting in unsatisfactory predictive performance. This limitation can lead to reduced accuracy and a potential failure to target as many potential homeowners as desired. Although the model yields good revenue figures, its generalizability may be compromised. Furthermore, the feature engineering aspect of the model could benefit from enhancements once a better understanding of the variables is gained. I believe the models performance could be improved with the inclusion of additional variables.
